# System Dependencies

If the agent needs system packages (e.g. `imagemagick`, `ffmpeg`, `poppler-utils`), create an `apt-deps.sh` at the agent root. **Never create or modify a Dockerfile** — Airlock generates it automatically.

The base image is **Debian trixie** — use `apt-get`. Don't clean the apt cache; Airlock handles that via BuildKit cache mounts.

Example `apt-deps.sh`:
```bash
apt-get update && apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends ffmpeg poppler-utils
```

The script runs in the agent's runtime image. To verify a binary behaves the way you expect (e.g. before writing `exec.Command("ffmpeg", ...)` into the agent), install it into your own builder env first:

```bash
sudo bash apt-deps.sh
ffmpeg -version
```

`sudo` is preconfigured for `apt-get`/`apt-cache` only — no password needed. Once you've verified the binary works, the same `apt-deps.sh` ships into the runtime image automatically.

Only create this file when the agent genuinely needs system packages not in the base image.

# Environment Rules

The build environment (Go toolchain, GOCACHE, GOMODCACHE, sqlc, templ) is pre-configured. If a build command fails due to permissions, missing tools, or broken cache — **do not attempt to fix the environment**. Do not create cache directories, install tools, or change environment variables. Report the error and stop. Environment problems are infrastructure issues, not code issues.

# Simple Example — Weather Agent

A minimal agent that fetches weather data via a public API:

```go
// --- file: main.go ---
package main

import (
    "context"
    "io"
    "net/http"

    "github.com/airlockrun/agentsdk"
    "github.com/dop251/goja"
)

func main() {
    agent := agentsdk.New(agentsdk.Config{
        Description: "Weather agent that fetches current conditions for any city",
    })

    type WeatherIn struct {
        City string `json:"city" jsonschema:"description=City name, e.g. London"`
    }
    type WeatherOut struct {
        Raw string `json:"raw"`
    }
    agent.RegisterTool(&agentsdk.Tool[WeatherIn, WeatherOut]{
        Name:        "get_weather",
        Description: "Get current weather for a city.",
        Execute: func(ctx context.Context, in WeatherIn) (WeatherOut, error) {
            resp, err := http.Get("https://wttr.in/" + in.City + "?format=j1")
            if err != nil {
                return WeatherOut{}, err
            }
            defer resp.Body.Close()
            body, _ := io.ReadAll(resp.Body)
            return WeatherOut{Raw: string(body)}, nil
        },
        Access: agentsdk.AccessUser,
    })

    agent.Serve()
}
```

That's it — the LLM can now call `get_weather({city: "London"})` in `run_js` and get back a typed object.

# Design Principle: Always Register Granular Tools

When building any feature (routes, crons, webhooks, connections), also register **granular tools** that give the LLM access to the same data and operations. Don't just build the direct implementation — expose the building blocks so the LLM can reason about and interact with the domain in conversations via `run_js`.

Bad: register only `importPlaylist` that bulk-inserts data into the DB. The LLM can import but can't inspect, search, or reason about the data.

Good: register `importPlaylist`, `listSongs`, `getSong`, `voteSong`. Now the LLM can answer "what songs did we import?", "which song has the most votes?", or "add my vote for track X" — all through `run_js`.

Think: "what would the LLM need to call to be a helpful conversational assistant in this domain?" and register those tools.

# Code Organization

**Keep main.go thin.** It should only contain registrations — no business logic.

Put implementation in separate packages under the agent directory:

```
agents/{agent_id}/
├── main.go                   # Registrations only
├── spotify/                  # Package for Spotify integration
│   ├── service.go            # Go types, API helpers using ConnectionHandle
│   └── vm.go                 # VM wrapper functions
└── ...
```

**Pattern:** Each domain gets its own package with two layers:
1. **Pure Go functions** — business logic, API calls, data transformation. Accept handles and plain Go types.
2. **VM wrappers** — thin functions that extract goja arguments, call the pure Go function, and convert the result back.

main.go imports the packages and registers the VM wrappers.

# Full Example — Spotify Agent with Deps

This shows the recommended pattern: handles, Deps, separate packages.

```go
// --- file: main.go ---
package main

import (
    "agent/spotify"
    "github.com/airlockrun/agentsdk"
)

func main() {
    agent := agentsdk.New(agentsdk.Config{
        Description: "Spotify agent for music playback control and search",
    })

    // RegisterConnection returns a *ConnectionHandle for type-safe API calls.
    spotifyConn := agent.RegisterConnection(spotify.Connection())

    // Store handles in Deps so any package can access them via GetDeps.
    agent.Deps = &spotify.Deps{Spotify: spotifyConn}

    // Register tools — typed In/Out structs defined in the spotify package.
    agent.RegisterTool(&agentsdk.Tool[spotify.SearchIn, spotify.SearchOut]{
        Name: "search_tracks", Description: "Search Spotify tracks.",
        Execute: spotify.SearchTracks, Access: agentsdk.AccessUser,
    })
    agent.RegisterTool(&agentsdk.Tool[struct{}, spotify.PlaybackState]{
        Name: "get_playback", Description: "Get current playback state.",
        Execute: spotify.GetPlayback, Access: agentsdk.AccessUser,
    })
    agent.RegisterTool(&agentsdk.Tool[spotify.PlayIn, spotify.PlayOut]{
        Name: "play", Description: "Start or resume playback.",
        Execute: spotify.Play, Access: agentsdk.AccessUser,
    })
    agent.RegisterTool(&agentsdk.Tool[struct{}, spotify.PauseOut]{
        Name: "pause", Description: "Pause playback.",
        Execute: spotify.Pause, Access: agentsdk.AccessUser,
    })

    agent.Serve()
}
```

```go
// --- file: spotify/deps.go ---
package spotify

import "github.com/airlockrun/agentsdk"

// Deps holds handles shared across all spotify functions.
// Set on agent.Deps in main.go, accessed via agentsdk.GetDeps[*Deps](ctx).
type Deps struct {
    Spotify *agentsdk.ConnectionHandle
}
```

```go
// --- file: spotify/connection.go ---
package spotify

import "github.com/airlockrun/agentsdk"

func Connection() *agentsdk.Connection {
    return &agentsdk.Connection{
        Slug:              "spotify",
        Name:              "Spotify",
        Description:       "Spotify Web API for music playback and search",
        AuthMode:          "oauth",
        AuthURL:           "https://accounts.spotify.com/authorize",
        TokenURL:          "https://accounts.spotify.com/api/token",
        BaseURL:           "https://api.spotify.com",
        Scopes:            []string{"user-read-playback-state", "user-modify-playback-state"},
        AuthInjection:     agentsdk.AuthInjection{Type: "bearer"},
        SetupInstructions: "Create a Spotify app at https://developer.spotify.com/dashboard, add the OAuth redirect URI from the connection settings page.",
        LLMHint:           "All Spotify API paths start with /v1/. Use the registered spotify functions instead of raw connection requests.",
        Access:            agentsdk.AccessUser,
    }
}
```

```go
// --- file: spotify/service.go ---
package spotify

import (
    "context"
    "encoding/json"
    "fmt"
    "net/url"

    "github.com/airlockrun/agentsdk"
)

type Track struct {
    Name   string `json:"name"`
    URI    string `json:"uri"`
    Artist string `json:"artist"`
}

type SearchResult struct {
    Tracks struct {
        Items []Track `json:"items"`
    } `json:"tracks"`
}

// SearchTracks searches Spotify tracks. Uses the connection handle from Deps.
func SearchTracks(ctx context.Context, conn *agentsdk.ConnectionHandle, query string, limit int) (*SearchResult, error) {
    if limit <= 0 {
        limit = 10
    }
    body, err := conn.Request(ctx, "GET",
        "/v1/search?type=track&limit="+fmt.Sprint(limit)+"&q="+url.QueryEscape(query),
        nil)
    if err != nil {
        return nil, err
    }
    var result SearchResult
    if err := json.Unmarshal(body, &result); err != nil {
        return nil, err
    }
    return &result, nil
}
```

```go
// --- file: spotify/tools.go ---
package spotify

import (
    "context"
    "encoding/json"

    "github.com/airlockrun/agentsdk"
)

type SearchIn struct {
    Query string `json:"query" jsonschema:"description=Search query"`
    Limit int    `json:"limit,omitempty" jsonschema:"minimum=1,maximum=50"`
}
type SearchOut struct {
    Tracks []Track `json:"tracks"`
}

func SearchTracks(ctx context.Context, in SearchIn) (SearchOut, error) {
    d := agentsdk.GetDeps[*Deps](ctx)
    return doSearch(ctx, d.Spotify, in.Query, in.Limit)
}

type PlaybackState map[string]any

func GetPlayback(ctx context.Context, _ struct{}) (PlaybackState, error) {
    d := agentsdk.GetDeps[*Deps](ctx)
    body, err := d.Spotify.Request(ctx, "GET", "/v1/me/player", nil)
    if err != nil {
        return nil, err
    }
    var out PlaybackState
    if len(body) > 0 {
        _ = json.Unmarshal(body, &out)
    }
    return out, nil
}

type PlayIn  struct { TrackURI string `json:"trackURI,omitempty"` }
type PlayOut struct { OK bool `json:"ok"` }

func Play(ctx context.Context, in PlayIn) (PlayOut, error) {
    d := agentsdk.GetDeps[*Deps](ctx)
    var body any
    if in.TrackURI != "" {
        body = map[string]any{"uris": []string{in.TrackURI}}
    }
    if _, err := d.Spotify.Request(ctx, "PUT", "/v1/me/player/play", body); err != nil {
        return PlayOut{}, err
    }
    return PlayOut{OK: true}, nil
}

type PauseOut struct { OK bool `json:"ok"` }

func Pause(ctx context.Context, _ struct{}) (PauseOut, error) {
    d := agentsdk.GetDeps[*Deps](ctx)
    if _, err := d.Spotify.Request(ctx, "PUT", "/v1/me/player/pause", nil); err != nil {
        return PauseOut{}, err
    }
    return PauseOut{OK: true}, nil
}
```

**Key patterns in this example:**
- `RegisterConnection` returns `*ConnectionHandle` — used for all API calls
- `agent.Deps` stores handles so any package can access them via `agentsdk.GetDeps[*Deps](ctx)`
- Tool handlers take typed `In` and return typed `Out` + `error` — no goja.
- Business logic uses `handle.Request(ctx, method, path, body)` — returns raw bytes; `json.Unmarshal` into your struct. Body is auto-encoded (struct → JSON, `[]byte`/`string` → as-is, `nil` → no body). Airlock injects credentials.
- `LLMHint` on the connection tells the runtime LLM how to use raw `conn_spotify.requestJSON()` correctly

# agentsdk API Reference

## Agent Creation and Lifecycle

```go
agent := agentsdk.New(agentsdk.Config{
    Description: "What this agent does — shown to users in the UI",
})
agent.Serve()  // starts HTTP server, blocks until shutdown
```

**Description is required** — panics if empty. Update it when adding or changing agent capabilities.

## Agent.Deps — Dependency Injection

Store handles and shared state so any package can access them:

```go
// Define your deps struct (in its own file or the domain package).
type Deps struct {
    Gmail   *agentsdk.ConnectionHandle
    GitHub  *agentsdk.MCPHandle
    Reports *agentsdk.TopicHandle
}

// In main.go — set after registering handles.
agent.Deps = &Deps{
    Gmail:   agent.RegisterConnection(&agentsdk.Connection{Slug: "gmail", /* ... */}),
    GitHub:  agent.RegisterMCP(&agentsdk.MCP{Slug: "github", /* ... */}),
    Reports: agent.RegisterTopic(&agentsdk.Topic{Slug: "reports", Description: "Weekly report notifications"}),
}

// In any handler — retrieve typed deps from the run.
func DoSomething(ctx context.Context, in SomeIn) (SomeOut, error) {
    d := agentsdk.GetDeps[*Deps](ctx) // panics if type mismatch
    // use d.Gmail, d.GitHub, d.Reports
    return SomeOut{}, nil
}
```

## RegisterTool — Expose typed capabilities to the LLM

The LLM has one tool (`run_js`) that executes JavaScript. `RegisterTool` exposes typed Go functions as globals in the JS runtime. Each tool is declared with **input and output struct types** — Airlock renders their JSON schemas as TypeScript signatures in the system prompt, and validates arguments before `Execute` runs.

**Signature:**

```go
type DoThingIn struct {
    Query string `json:"query" jsonschema:"description=Search text"`
    Limit int    `json:"limit,omitempty" jsonschema:"minimum=1,maximum=50"`
}
type DoThingOut struct {
    Hits []string `json:"hits"`
}

agent.RegisterTool(&agentsdk.Tool[DoThingIn, DoThingOut]{
    Name:        "do_thing",
    Description: "Short, action-oriented summary of what this tool does.",
    Execute: func(ctx context.Context, in DoThingIn) (DoThingOut, error) {
        // in.Query and in.Limit are already decoded and typed.
        // Call agent.LLM(ctx, ...), storage helpers, etc. using ctx.
        // Return the typed Out — the SDK marshals it to JSON for the JS caller.
        return DoThingOut{Hits: []string{"one", "two"}}, nil
    },
    Access: agentsdk.AccessUser,
})
```

The LLM sees this in its system prompt as:

```typescript
/** Short, action-oriented summary of what this tool does. */
declare function do_thing(args: {
  query: string;       // Search text
  limit?: number;
}): {
  hits: string[];
};
```

and calls it inside `run_js` as `do_thing({query: "foo", limit: 5})`, receiving a native JS object `{hits: [...]}`.

**Naming convention.** Name tools in `snake_case` to match LLM tool-calling conventions and MCP (e.g. `search_tracks`, `get_weather`). Built-in VM bindings (`queryDB`, `printToUser`, `httpRequest`, `mcp_*.callTool`, `readFile`, `writeFile`, etc.) are `camelCase` (or `snake_case_prefix.camelCaseMethod` for namespaced ones) by design — that's how the LLM can tell a platform primitive from an agent-declared tool at a glance.

**Rules for `In` / `Out` struct types:**
- Fields need `json` tags. Add `jsonschema:"description=..."` for per-field docs visible to the LLM.
- Use `omitempty` on optional fields — they render with `?` in the TypeScript signature.
- Prefer `string` over `time.Time` for dates (RFC3339 strings). `json.Unmarshal` only accepts RFC3339 for `time.Time` and that surprises the LLM.
- No recursive types (the schema generator can't detect cycles). Use `json:"-"` on fields that would close the cycle.
- Binary data goes through `FileInfo` / the file API (`agent.WriteFile` + return the resulting `FileInfo`), not base64 strings in Out.

**Error handling:** return `error` from `Execute`. The SDK converts it to a JavaScript `throw` inside `run_js` — the LLM sees the `err.Error()` text and can react. Do not panic.

**Access levels** (set via `Tool.Access`):
- `agentsdk.AccessUser` — available to agent members (default if omitted).
- `agentsdk.AccessAdmin` — available only to agent owner/admins.
- `agentsdk.AccessPublic` — available to anyone (public prompts, bots).

**Input examples (optional).** Set `InputExamples: []In{...}` to render `@example` JSDoc lines alongside the signature. Useful when the schema alone doesn't convey realistic usage.

**No goja.** You never touch `*goja.Runtime`, `goja.FunctionCall`, `vm.ToValue`, or `vm.NewGoError`. The SDK handles all VM boundary concerns — you write plain typed Go.

## AddExtraPrompt — Access-scoped system prompt fragments

Airlock already renders a rich base system prompt for every run. It covers:
- The `run_js` tool and how to use it
- All registered tools visible to the caller, with typed TypeScript signatures
- MCP tools and connection request helpers
- Safety guards for public callers (no computation-heavy JS, no destructive ops without confirmation, etc.)
- Environment context (date, platform, conversation id)

**Do NOT re-declare any of the above.** `AddExtraPrompt` is only for content the baseline cannot infer on its own:
- The agent's persona, tone, or voice
- Domain-specific rules the LLM can't deduce from the tool signatures alone
- Per-access behavior differences the user explicitly asked for

**Signature:**

```go
agent.AddExtraPrompt(&agentsdk.ExtraPrompt{Text: "You are a concise events assistant for the Berlin meetup. Answer in English."})
agent.AddExtraPrompt(&agentsdk.ExtraPrompt{
    Text:   "When an admin asks to reset the attendee list, call resetAttendees() — always confirm first.",
    Access: []agentsdk.Access{agentsdk.AccessAdmin},
})
agent.AddExtraPrompt(&agentsdk.ExtraPrompt{
    Text:   "Public callers: only answer questions about event times and location. Decline anything else politely.",
    Access: []agentsdk.Access{agentsdk.AccessPublic},
})
```

Multiple calls accumulate; fragments appear in registration order. Empty `Access` slice makes the fragment visible to every caller. Access is filtered per-run based on the triggering user's membership — a public caller never sees fragments scoped to `AccessUser` or `AccessAdmin`.

**Access mapping** — same enum as `RegisterTool`/`RegisterRoute`:
- `agentsdk.AccessAdmin` — agent owner and admin members
- `agentsdk.AccessUser` — invited members
- `agentsdk.AccessPublic` — unauthenticated public callers
- (empty slice) — applied for every caller

**Scope:** extras apply only to chat-style runs (web UI and bridge drivers like Telegram). Webhook and cron triggers invoke your Go handler directly and never build a system prompt, so `AddExtraPrompt` has no effect on them — any LLM call you make from those handlers builds its own prompt in code.

**When NOT to call it:**
- The agent has no unusual persona and no per-access behavior — the baseline is enough.
- You're tempted to remind the LLM about `run_js`, registered functions, or public safety — the baseline already covers these.
- The instruction belongs in a specific function's description instead (the LLM reads those too).

## RegisterWebhook — Handle incoming webhooks

```go
agent.RegisterWebhook(&agentsdk.Webhook{
    Path: "github",
    Handler: func(ctx context.Context, data []byte, ew *agentsdk.EventWriter) error {
        // data is the raw request body
        return nil
    },
    Verify:      "hmac",                   // "hmac", "token", or "none" (default)
    Header:      "X-Hub-Signature-256",    // header for verification
    Description: "GitHub push events",
    Access:      agentsdk.AccessUser,
})
```

## RegisterCron — Scheduled jobs

```go
agent.RegisterCron(&agentsdk.Cron{
    Name:     "daily-report",
    Schedule: "0 9 * * *",
    Handler: func(ctx context.Context, ew *agentsdk.EventWriter) error {
        // runs at 9am daily
        return nil
    },
    Description: "Generate and send daily report",
})
```

## RegisterRoute — Custom HTTP routes

Serve API endpoints or HTML pages directly from the agent. Routes are proxied via the agent's subdomain.

```go
agent.RegisterRoute(&agentsdk.Route{
    Method: "GET",
    Path:   "/api/data",
    Handler: func(ctx context.Context, w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
        json.NewEncoder(w).Encode(map[string]string{"status": "ok"})
    },
    Access:      agentsdk.AccessUser,
    Description: "Get data",
})
```

**Always provide a Description** for routes — it tells users and the execution agent what each route does.

**Access levels** (set via `Route.Access`):
- `agentsdk.AccessUser` — **default choice.** Any user the agent has been shared with (enforced by Airlock). Use this unless there's a specific reason not to.
- `agentsdk.AccessAdmin` — agent owner and users with admin role. Use for destructive, sensitive, or admin-context operations (e.g. config, delete, reset).
- `agentsdk.AccessPublic` — no auth, anyone can reach the route. **Only use when the user explicitly asks for a public-facing page** (e.g. "make a public voting page", "a page anyone can see"). Never default to public.

## templ + htmx — HTML UI

Agents use [templ](https://templ.guide) for type-safe HTML components and [htmx](https://htmx.org) for interactivity. The scaffold includes a `views/` directory with a layout and index page. htmx is loaded from CDN in the layout.

templ files are compiled by `templ generate` (runs automatically during Docker build). Each `.templ` file produces a `_templ.go` file with Go functions you call from routes.

**Before running ANY Go command (`go mod tidy`, `go build`, `go vet`, `go test` — anything), run `go tool templ generate` first.** The scaffolded `views/` directory contains only `.templ` source files; Go's toolchain ignores those, sees an empty package, and reports misleading errors like "package agent/views is not in std" or "cannot find module providing package agent/views". `templ generate` produces the `_templ.go` files that make the package valid. Re-run it whenever you add or modify any `.templ` file. The Docker build re-runs it during image build, so you do not need to commit the generated files.

**Registering a templ page as a route:**

```go
import (
    "github.com/a-h/templ"
    "agent/views"
)

agent.RegisterRoute(&agentsdk.Route{
    Method: "GET",
    Path:   "/",
    Handler: func(ctx context.Context, w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
        templ.Handler(views.Index()).ServeHTTP(w, r)
    },
    Access:      agentsdk.AccessPublic,
    Description: "Homepage",
})
```

**templ component with htmx:**

```
// --- file: views/search.templ ---
package views

templ SearchForm() {
    <form hx-get="/search" hx-target="#results" hx-indicator="#spinner">
        <input type="text" name="q" placeholder="Search..."/>
        <button type="submit">Search</button>
        <span id="spinner" class="htmx-indicator">Loading...</span>
    </form>
    <div id="results"></div>
}

templ SearchResults(items []string) {
    <ul>
        for _, item := range items {
            <li>{ item }</li>
        }
    </ul>
}
```

**Returning an htmx partial from a route handler:**

```go
agent.RegisterRoute(&agentsdk.Route{
    Method: "GET",
    Path:   "/search",
    Handler: func(ctx context.Context, w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
        q := r.URL.Query().Get("q")
        results := doSearch(ctx, q) // your business logic
        views.SearchResults(results).Render(ctx, w)
    },
    Access:      agentsdk.AccessUser,
    Description: "Search results partial",
})
```

**Key patterns:**
- Full page loads use `@Layout("Title") { ... }` to wrap content in the HTML shell
- htmx requests get partial HTML (just the component, no layout) — htmx swaps it into the DOM
- Use `hx-get`/`hx-post` to call agent routes, `hx-target` to specify where the response goes
- Use `hx-trigger`, `hx-swap`, `hx-indicator` for loading states and fine-grained control
- templ components are type-safe Go functions — pass data as arguments, use `for`/`if` for logic

## RegisterConnection — Outgoing service connections

Returns `*ConnectionHandle` for type-safe proxied API calls.

```go
spotify := agent.RegisterConnection(&agentsdk.Connection{
    Slug:          "spotify",
    Name:          "Spotify",
    Description:   "Spotify Web API for music playback and search",
    AuthMode:      "oauth",
    AuthURL:       "https://accounts.spotify.com/authorize",
    TokenURL:      "https://accounts.spotify.com/api/token",
    BaseURL:       "https://api.spotify.com",
    Scopes:        []string{"user-read-playback-state", "user-modify-playback-state"},
    AuthInjection: agentsdk.AuthInjection{Type: "bearer"},
    LLMHint:       "All Spotify API paths start with /v1/.",
    Access:        agentsdk.AccessUser,
})

// Use the handle in Go code:
body, err := spotify.Request(ctx, "GET", "/v1/me/player", nil)         // no body, returns raw JSON bytes
spotify.Request(ctx, "PUT", "/v1/me/player", myStruct)                  // struct → JSON body
spotify.Request(ctx, "PUT", "/v1/me/player/pause", nil)                 // no body, no response decode needed
```

**LLMHint** is injected into the `run_js` tool description so the runtime LLM knows how to use the connection correctly (e.g., required path prefixes). Always set this when the API has non-obvious conventions.

**AuthMode values:** `"oauth"`, `"token"`, `"none"`

**AuthInjection types:**
- `"bearer"` — Authorization: Bearer {token}
- `"api_key_header"` — Custom header (set Name to header name, e.g. "X-API-Key")
- `"bot_token_url_prefix"` — Token prepended to URL path (e.g. Telegram bot API)

## RegisterMCP — MCP Server Dependencies

Returns `*MCPHandle` for calling tools from Go. The runtime LLM accesses MCP tools via JS objects: `mcp_{slug}.listTools()` and `mcp_{slug}.callTool(name, args)`.

```go
github := agent.RegisterMCP(&agentsdk.MCP{
    Slug:     "github",
    Name:     "GitHub",
    URL:      "https://api.githubcopilot.com/mcp",
    AuthMode: "oauth_discovery",  // RFC 9728 auto-discovery
    Access:   agentsdk.AccessUser,
})

// Use the handle in Go code:
result, _ := github.CallTool(ctx, "search_repos", map[string]any{"query": "test"})
tools, _ := github.ListTools(ctx)
```

**AuthMode values:** `"oauth_discovery"` (RFC 9728/8414 auto), `"oauth"` (manual URLs), `"token"` (static secret), `"none"` (no auth)

Use the `mcp_probe` tool to check what a URL supports before writing RegisterMCP code.

## RegisterModel — Named model slots

Declare a named slot for every distinct runtime LLM use case. The admin picks a specific model for each slot in the Airlock UI (Agent → Models tab). At runtime the slug resolves via three tiers:

1. Slot binding (admin's chosen model for that slug)
2. Per-agent capability override (Models tab → "Capability Overrides")
3. System default (Settings → Default Models)

Undeclared slugs still work — they fall through to the capability default and then the system default — but they don't appear in the admin UI, so you lose the ability to rebind them. Declare slots for any call that should be independently configurable.

**Signature:**

```go
agent.RegisterModel(&agentsdk.ModelSlot{
    Slug:        "summarize",
    Capability:  agentsdk.CapText,
    Description: "Short summaries for weekly reports",
})
// Later, in a handler:
model := agent.LLM(ctx, "summarize", agentsdk.ModelOpts{})
```

Capabilities map to the SDK method and correspond to the admin UI capability rows:

- `CapText` / `CapVision` → `agent.LLM(ctx, slug, agentsdk.ModelOpts{Capability: ...})`
- `CapImage` → `agent.ImageModel(ctx, slug, ...)`
- `CapSpeech` → `agent.SpeechModel(ctx, slug, ...)` (TTS)
- `CapTranscription` → `agent.TranscriptionModel(ctx, slug, ...)` (STT)
- `CapEmbedding` → `agent.EmbeddingModel(ctx, slug, ...)`

The built-in VM helpers (`transcribeAudio`, `generateImage`, `generateSpeech`, `embed`) use empty slugs intentionally — they resolve via the per-agent capability override + system default, no slot needed.

## RegisterTopic — Notification Topics

Returns `*TopicHandle` for publishing notifications from Go code (crons, webhooks). Users subscribe via the UI; the runtime LLM can subscribe the current conversation via `topic_{slug}.subscribe()`.

```go
alerts := agent.RegisterTopic(&agentsdk.Topic{
    Slug:        "alerts",
    Description: "System alerts and notifications",
    Access:      agentsdk.AccessUser,
})

// Publish from a cron or webhook handler:
alerts.Publish(ctx, []agentsdk.DisplayPart{
    {Type: "text", Text: "Daily report is ready"},
    {Type: "file", Source: "reports/daily.pdf", Filename: "report.pdf"},
})
```

## RegisterDirectory — Unix-style file storage

The platform exposes file storage as a flat unix-like filesystem. The
agent registers absolute directories (e.g. `/reports`, `/uploads`) and
the LLM uses top-level functions to operate on absolute paths. There is
no zone slug, no `{zone, key}` shape, no per-directory namespace object —
everything is just paths.

```go
agent.RegisterDirectory("/uploads", agentsdk.DirectoryOpts{
    Read:        agentsdk.AccessUser,
    Write:       agentsdk.AccessUser,
    List:        agentsdk.AccessUser,
    Description: "Files the user uploaded in chat.",
})
agent.RegisterDirectory("/reports", agentsdk.DirectoryOpts{
    Read:        agentsdk.AccessUser,   // anyone in the agent can read
    Write:       agentsdk.AccessAdmin,  // only owners write
    List:        agentsdk.AccessUser,
    Description: "Generated reports.",
})
agent.RegisterDirectory("/cache", agentsdk.DirectoryOpts{
    Read:        agentsdk.AccessInternal,  // builder-only — never visible to LLM
    Write:       agentsdk.AccessInternal,
    List:        agentsdk.AccessInternal,
    Description: "Memoized API responses.",
})
```

`Read`, `Write`, and `List` are independent caps. `delete` folds into
`Write` (POSIX-style: write on the parent governs unlink). Each cap can
be set to `AccessAdmin`, `AccessUser`, `AccessPublic`, or
`AccessInternal`. `AccessInternal` directories are **unreachable from
the LLM and from the public HTTP route** — only trusted builder Go code
that constructs the path itself can read or write them.

The framework auto-registers **`/tmp`** at `Read=Write=List=AccessUser`
for scratch (truncated tool output, generated media). You may
`RegisterDirectory("/tmp", DirectoryOpts{Description: "..."})` to
customize the description; the access caps stay at the framework's
defaults.

### Trusted Go file API — for builder code that constructs paths

```go
src, err := agent.OpenFile(ctx, "/uploads/doc.pdf")          // io.ReadCloser
data, err := agent.ReadFile(ctx, "/uploads/notes.txt")       // []byte
info, err := agent.WriteFile(ctx, "/reports/q1.csv", reader, "text/csv")
info, err := agent.StatFile(ctx, "/uploads/doc.pdf")         // FileInfo
files, err := agent.ListDir(ctx, "/uploads/", agentsdk.ListOpts{Recursive: false})
err := agent.DeleteFile(ctx, "/reports/old.csv")             // idempotent
err := agent.CopyFile(ctx, "/uploads/in.csv", "/reports/copy.csv")
```

These methods **do not call `CheckFileAccess`**. They're the trusted
path: the builder is constructing the path themselves, so we trust
them. Use them freely from cron handlers, webhook handlers, internal
caches, anywhere your Go code knows the path it wants.

### Untrusted paths — when a tool accepts a path from the LLM

If a tool's input declares a `string` field for a file (e.g. the LLM
asks "crop this image"), the path is **untrusted** — the LLM can pass
any string, including one pointing under an internal directory or with
`..` segments. **You must call `agent.CheckFileAccess` before using the
path anywhere**, including before passing it to an external API that
won't read the bytes itself but might leak its existence.

```go
type CropIn struct {
    Image  string `json:"image"`   // absolute path supplied by the LLM
    X, Y   int
    W, H   int
}
type CropOut struct {
    Result agentsdk.FileInfo `json:"result"` // {path, filename, contentType, size, lastModified}
}

agent.RegisterTool(&agentsdk.Tool[CropIn, CropOut]{
    Name:        "crop_image",
    Description: "Crop a stored image and save the result.",
    Access:      agentsdk.AccessUser,
    Execute: func(ctx context.Context, in CropIn) (CropOut, error) {
        // Always check untrusted paths first.
        if err := agent.CheckFileAccess(ctx, in.Image, agentsdk.OpRead); err != nil {
            return CropOut{}, err
        }
        src, err := agent.OpenFile(ctx, in.Image)
        if err != nil {
            return CropOut{}, err
        }
        defer src.Close()
        cropped := crop(src, in.X, in.Y, in.W, in.H)
        outPath := "/tmp/crop-" + randHex(4) + ".png"
        info, err := agent.WriteFile(ctx, outPath, bytes.NewReader(cropped), "image/png")
        if err != nil {
            return CropOut{}, err
        }
        return CropOut{Result: info}, nil
    },
})
```

`CheckFileAccess` returns `agentsdk.ErrNotFound` for both "denied" and
"no covering directory" — never distinguish them; the indistinguishable
response prevents path-guessing from leaking what exists.

### Directories surface as URLs on the agent's subdomain

Directories with `Read != AccessInternal` are reachable at
`https://{slug}.{agentDomain}/__air/storage{path}` — e.g.
`/reports/q1.csv` becomes `https://myagent.example.com/__air/storage/reports/q1.csv`.

- `AccessPublic` — served unauthenticated. Anyone with the URL.
- `AccessUser` — requires the user to be logged in with agent
  membership. The proxy redirects through the relay-login flow when
  no cookie is set, so a click in chat just prompts sign-in and
  lands back on the file.
- `AccessAdmin` — same, but admin role required.
- `AccessInternal` — never served (404).

## Agent Methods (ctx-first — call from any handler)

Every handler — RegisterTool (via `Tool.Execute`), RegisterWebhook,
RegisterCron, RegisterRoute — receives a `context.Context` as its first
argument. Pass it straight through to any `agent.*(ctx, ...)` call. Model
calls and `agent.Log` are automatically tracked in the Runs UI for
whichever handler invoked them; you never construct or complete a Run
yourself.

```go
// LLM + media — all take ctx-first
model := agent.LLM(ctx, slug, agentsdk.ModelOpts{})                 // streaming language model
agent.ImageModel(ctx, slug, agentsdk.ModelOpts{})                   // image generation
agent.SpeechModel(ctx, slug, agentsdk.ModelOpts{})                  // text-to-speech
agent.TranscriptionModel(ctx, slug, agentsdk.ModelOpts{})           // speech-to-text
agent.EmbeddingModel(ctx, slug, agentsdk.ModelOpts{})               // embeddings

// Logging — appended to the current run (visible in the Runs UI);
// falls through to process zap log if no run is bound. The level
// argument controls how the run UI surfaces the entry.
agent.Log(ctx, agentsdk.LogLevelInfo, "imported 42 rows")
agent.Log(ctx, agentsdk.LogLevelWarn, "skipping malformed row")
agent.Log(ctx, agentsdk.LogLevelError, "import failed: " + err.Error())
agent.Logf(ctx, agentsdk.LogLevelInfo, "imported %d rows", n)   // printf-style sibling

// Storage — flat unix-style file API. Builder Go code is trusted: these
// methods do NOT call CheckFileAccess. For paths that arrive from the LLM
// (e.g. tool input), call agent.CheckFileAccess(ctx, path, op) first.
agent.OpenFile(ctx, "/uploads/doc.pdf")              // (io.ReadCloser, error)
agent.ReadFile(ctx, "/uploads/notes.txt")            // ([]byte, error)
agent.WriteFile(ctx, "/reports/q1.csv", reader, "text/csv")  // (FileInfo, error)
agent.StatFile(ctx, "/reports/q1.csv")               // (FileInfo, error)
agent.ListDir(ctx, "/reports/", agentsdk.ListOpts{}) // ([]FileInfo, error)
agent.DeleteFile(ctx, "/reports/old.csv")            // idempotent
agent.CopyFile(ctx, "/uploads/in.csv", "/reports/copy.csv")  // cross-directory
agent.CheckFileAccess(ctx, llmPath, agentsdk.OpRead) // gate paths from untrusted sources
agent.DB()                                           // *agentsdk.AgentDB — pass to sqlc-generated New() (nil if AIRLOCK_DB_URL unset)
```

Inside a tool's `Execute` body you get typed `ctx` and the decoded `In`
struct — no goja boilerplate. Return `(Out, error)`:

```go
Execute: func(ctx context.Context, in ExampleIn) (ExampleOut, error) {
    result, err := doWork(ctx, in.Arg)
    if err != nil {
        return ExampleOut{}, err  // surfaces as a JS throw inside run_js
    }
    return ExampleOut{Result: result}, nil
},
```

Connection handles (`*ConnectionHandle`) and MCP handles (`*MCPHandle`) take
`ctx` and Airlock injects credentials automatically. The connection **path**
is appended to `BaseURL`.

## Using LLM from Agent Code (goai)

Agents can call language models from Go code (crons, webhooks, VM functions) via `agent.LLM(ctx, slug, def)` and the `goai` package. LLM calls are proxied through Airlock so token usage is tracked.

### GenerateText — freeform text or structured output (with optional tools)

`goai.GenerateText` is the single entry point for both natural language and structured output. Set `Output` to switch between modes; tools and structured output can be combined.

**Plain text:**

```go
import (
    "github.com/airlockrun/goai"
    "github.com/airlockrun/goai/message"
    "github.com/airlockrun/goai/stream"
)

type SummarizeIn struct {
    Text string `json:"text"`
}
type SummarizeOut struct {
    Summary string `json:"summary"`
}

func Summarize(ctx context.Context, in SummarizeIn) (SummarizeOut, error) {
    model := agentsdk.AgentFromContext(ctx).LLM(ctx, "summarize", agentsdk.ModelDef{Description: "Text summarization"})

    result, err := goai.GenerateText(ctx, stream.Input{
        Model: model,
        Messages: []message.Message{
            message.NewSystemMessage("You are a concise summarizer. Respond with 2-3 sentences."),
            message.NewUserMessage("Summarize this: " + in.Text),
        },
    })
    if err != nil {
        return SummarizeOut{}, err
    }
    return SummarizeOut{Summary: result.Text}, nil
}
```

**Structured output via `output.Object`:**

```go
import (
    "github.com/airlockrun/goai"
    "github.com/airlockrun/goai/message"
    "github.com/airlockrun/goai/output"
    "github.com/airlockrun/goai/schema"
    "github.com/airlockrun/goai/stream"
)

type SentimentResult struct {
    Sentiment  string  `json:"sentiment" description:"positive, negative, or neutral"`
    Confidence float64 `json:"confidence" description:"0.0 to 1.0"`
    Reasoning  string  `json:"reasoning" description:"Brief explanation"`
}

type SentimentIn struct {
    Text string `json:"text"`
}

func AnalyzeSentiment(ctx context.Context, in SentimentIn) (SentimentResult, error) {
    model := agentsdk.AgentFromContext(ctx).LLM(ctx, "sentiment", agentsdk.ModelDef{Description: "Sentiment analysis"})

    result, err := goai.GenerateText(ctx, stream.Input{
        Model: model,
        Output: output.Object(output.ObjectOptions{
            Schema: schema.MustFromType(SentimentResult{}),
            Name:   "SentimentResult",
        }),
        Messages: []message.Message{
            message.NewUserMessage("Analyze the sentiment of this text: " + in.Text),
        },
    })
    if err != nil {
        return SentimentResult{}, err
    }
    raw, _ := json.Marshal(result.Output)
    var sentiment SentimentResult
    _ = json.Unmarshal(raw, &sentiment)
    return sentiment, nil
}
```

`schema.MustFromType()` generates the JSON schema from struct tags. When `Output` is set, goai sends the schema to the model on every step and parses the final response when the model finishes with `stop`. Tools and structured output can be combined: the model calls tools first, then produces structured output on the final step.

Other output strategies: `output.Array(...)`, `output.Choice(...)`, `output.JSON(...)`, `output.Text()` (default).

## Built-in VM Bindings (DO NOT re-register)

These are already registered by agentsdk for every run. Do NOT declare them as tools — they exist automatically:

- `conn_{slug}.request(method, path, body?)` → string — raw HTTP via connection
- `conn_{slug}.requestJSON(method, path, body?)` → object — JSON HTTP via connection
- `mcp_{slug}.callTool(toolName, args?)` → result — call MCP tool
- `mcp_{slug}.listTools()` → [{name, description, inputSchema}, ...] — discover MCP tools
- `queryDB(sql, ...params)` → [{...}, ...]
- `execDB(sql, ...params)` → {rowsAffected: N}
- `readFile(path)` → string — read a file as UTF-8 text (CSV, JSON, HTML, source)
- `readBytes(path)` → Uint8Array — read a file as binary bytes (images, PDFs)
- `writeFile(path, data, contentType?)` → FileInfo — `data` is a string or Uint8Array; `contentType` is optional (auto-detected from extension)
- `listDir(path, opts?)` → FileInfo[] — non-recursive by default; pass `{recursive: true}` to walk the subtree
- `statFile(path)` → FileInfo — `{path, filename, contentType, size, lastModified}`
- `fileExists(path)` → boolean
- `deleteFile(path)` — idempotent
- `/tmp` — framework-owned scratch directory, always present at user-level access; used for truncated tool output and generated media
- `attachToContext(path)` → string — load a stored image/file into the LLM's visual context for the next turn
- `printToUser(parts)` — send rich content to user; parts is single object or array of {type, text, source, url, data, filename, mimeType, alt, duration} — `source` is an absolute path string
- `topic_{slug}.subscribe()` / `topic_{slug}.unsubscribe()` — subscribe/unsubscribe current conversation to a notification topic
- `log(message)`
- `webSearch(query, count?)` → {results: [{title, url, snippet}], synthesis?, provider}
- `webFetch(url, format?)` → {content, contentType, url, statusCode} — format: 'markdown' (default), 'text', 'html'
- `httpRequest(url, opts?)` → {status, headers, body, contentType, size, savedTo?} — raw HTTP. opts: {method, headers, body, timeout, saveAs, raw}. `saveAs` is an absolute path string. `savedTo` (when present) is an absolute path string — pass directly to readFile() or attachToContext().

## Database Access

If the agent needs its own database tables:

1. Create migration files in `db/migrations/` (e.g. `00001_init.sql`)
2. Create query files in `db/queries/` (e.g. `queries.sql`)
3. Run `sqlc generate` — generates Go code in `internal/db/`
4. Import `internal/db` in your Go code

Migrations run automatically at container startup via **goose**. Each file has both Up and Down sections in a single `.sql` file:

```sql
-- +goose Up
CREATE TABLE rooms (
    id   uuid PRIMARY KEY DEFAULT gen_random_uuid(),
    name text NOT NULL
);

-- +goose Down
DROP TABLE rooms;
```

**Numbering:** use zero-padded prefixes like `00001_init.sql`, `00002_add_users.sql`. Goose runs them in numeric order.

**Go migrations for operational work:** If you need to do something that can't be expressed in SQL — rename S3 keys, backfill data via HTTP, etc. — create a `.go` file in the same `db/migrations/` package. Retrieve the agent from the migration context via `agentsdk.AgentFromMigrationContext(ctx)` to call storage/API methods.

**Tx vs NoTx — pick the right registration helper:**
- `goose.AddMigrationContext(up, down)` — wraps your function in a Postgres transaction (signature: `func(ctx, tx *sql.Tx) error`). Default choice for short, DB-focused work; partial failures roll back atomically. The wrapping transaction is harmless even when you do zero SQL (~2ms overhead for an empty BEGIN/COMMIT).
- `goose.AddMigrationNoTxContext(up, down)` — runs without a wrapping transaction (signature: `func(ctx, db *sql.DB) error`). Use this when you (1) call slow external services like S3 / HTTP — you don't want a Postgres transaction held open for the duration, idle-in-transaction blocks autovacuum and holds locks; or (2) need operations Postgres won't run in a transaction (`CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY`, `ALTER TYPE ... ADD VALUE` on older PG, `VACUUM`).

The example below renames S3 keys, so it uses `NoTxContext` — the loop could take minutes on a real bucket and we don't want the DB transaction held that whole time.

```go
// db/migrations/00002_rename_media.go
package migrations

import (
	"context"
	"database/sql"
	"path"

	"github.com/airlockrun/agentsdk"
	"github.com/pressly/goose/v3"
)

func init() {
	// NoTx: this migration calls S3 in a loop; don't hold a Postgres tx open across slow external calls.
	goose.AddMigrationNoTxContext(Up00002, Down00002)
}

func Up00002(ctx context.Context, db *sql.DB) error {
	// Build-time validation runs migrations against a test DB without S3,
	// Airlock API, or connection credentials. Guard side effects so
	// validation still exercises the SQL portion that later migrations
	// may depend on.
	if agentsdk.IsValidatingMigrations() {
		return nil
	}

	agent := agentsdk.AgentFromMigrationContext(ctx)
	agent.RegisterDirectory("/old", agentsdk.DirectoryOpts{Read: agentsdk.AccessAdmin, Write: agentsdk.AccessAdmin, List: agentsdk.AccessAdmin})
	agent.RegisterDirectory("/media", agentsdk.DirectoryOpts{Read: agentsdk.AccessUser, Write: agentsdk.AccessUser, List: agentsdk.AccessUser})
	files, err := agent.ListDir(ctx, "/old/", agentsdk.ListOpts{Recursive: true})
	if err != nil {
		return err
	}
	for _, f := range files {
		dst := "/media/" + path.Base(f.Path)
		if err := agent.CopyFile(ctx, f.Path, dst); err != nil {
			return err
		}
		if err := agent.DeleteFile(ctx, f.Path); err != nil {
			return err
		}
	}
	return nil
}

func Down00002(ctx context.Context, db *sql.DB) error {
	return nil
}
```

`main.go` already blank-imports `db/migrations`, so `init()` fires automatically and goose picks up the registered functions.

**Guard external side effects in Go migrations.** Build-time validation runs the full migration chain up → down → up against a test DB clone. It does NOT have access to S3, the Airlock API, or connection credentials. Any Go migration that touches external services must check `agentsdk.IsValidatingMigrations()` and return early for side effects — but still run any DB/schema work so that subsequent SQL migrations relying on it can be validated.

**After creating migration files, always validate them:**

```bash
# Validate SQL migrations: up → down → up
goose -dir db/migrations postgres "$TEST_DB_URL" up
goose -dir db/migrations postgres "$TEST_DB_URL" reset
goose -dir db/migrations postgres "$TEST_DB_URL" up

# Inspect the resulting schema
psql "$TEST_DB_PSQL" -c "SET search_path TO $TEST_DB_SCHEMA; SELECT table_name FROM information_schema.tables WHERE table_schema = '$TEST_DB_SCHEMA'"
```

Three env vars are available: `TEST_DB_URL` (for goose), `TEST_DB_PSQL` (for psql, no search_path), `TEST_DB_SCHEMA` (schema name). If `$TEST_DB_URL` is not set, skip validation.

The agent gets its own PostgreSQL schema. Use standard SQL. The generated Go code uses pgx/v5.

**Using sqlc in Go code:**

```go
db := agent.DB()                    // same handle from any handler
queries := internaldb.New(db)       // import "agent/internal/db" as internaldb
users, err := queries.ListActiveUsers(ctx)
```

**Always use sqlc for Go code.** Never write raw `db.QueryRow`/`db.Exec` SQL strings in Go — use sqlc queries for type safety and maintainability. The `queryDB`/`execDB` VM bindings exist only for the runtime LLM's JavaScript — they are NOT a pattern for Go code.

# Build Verification

After writing code, always verify it compiles:

```bash
cd agents/{agent_id} && go mod tidy && go build -buildvcs=false -o /tmp/agent .
```

Only run `sqlc generate` if you created `.sql` files in `db/queries/`. If the agent doesn't use the database, skip sqlc entirely.

If the build fails, fix the errors and try again.

# Rules

1. Read AGENT_SPEC.md first — it contains all requirements
2. Write idiomatic Go — proper error handling, no unused imports
3. Keep main.go thin — registrations only, business logic in separate packages
4. Use `RegisterTool` for LLM-callable capabilities. Define a Go `In` struct with `json` + `jsonschema` tags, an `Out` struct, and an `Execute(ctx, In) (Out, error)` handler. No goja — the SDK handles the VM boundary.
5. Use RegisterWebhook/RegisterCron for event handlers (pure Go, no VM boundary)
6. Use RegisterConnection for external services — decide what services are needed from the description
7. Never hardcode credentials — use connection handles (`conn.Request(ctx, method, path, body)`) with Airlock-managed auth
8. Use Agent.Deps + GetDeps[T] to pass handles across packages
9. Keep function descriptions clear and concise — the LLM reads them
10. Verify compilation before committing
11. Set a clear Description in agentsdk.Config — it's shown to users in the UI
12. Never create or modify a Dockerfile — use apt-deps.sh for system dependencies
13. Only call AddExtraPrompt for agent-specific persona, domain rules, or explicit per-access behavior — Airlock's base prompt already covers run_js, registered functions, MCP tools, and public-caller safety guards
14. If you need to use the real filesystem (e.g. to exec ffmpeg or similar tools), use it briefly — clean up the files after you use them or upload them to S3. Otherwise the container's FS will keep growing.
15. Declare a slot with `RegisterModel` for any LLM call the admin should be able to rebind independently (summarization, routing decisions, per-task specialists). Bare `agent.XxxModel(ctx, "", ...)` calls use the per-agent capability default and are fine when no per-task override is needed.
